1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:04,400
This video is sponsored by

2
00:00:02,120 --> 00:00:06,319
Flexispot. Concurrency is a recurring

3
00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:08,960
topic on this channel. It's the

4
00:00:06,319 --> 00:00:10,719
technique alongside CPU scheduling that

5
00:00:08,960 --> 00:00:13,440
distributes computing resources among

6
00:00:10,719 --> 00:00:15,519
multiple executable entities. The system

7
00:00:13,440 --> 00:00:17,119
switches the CPU between them so quickly

8
00:00:15,519 --> 00:00:19,680
that it creates the illusion they are

9
00:00:17,119 --> 00:00:21,760
all running at once. When these

10
00:00:19,680 --> 00:00:24,320
processes operate independently,

11
00:00:21,760 --> 00:00:26,080
everything tends to work smoothly. But

12
00:00:24,320 --> 00:00:28,560
the moment concurrent entities need to

13
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:30,640
interact, things can get tricky and if

14
00:00:28,560 --> 00:00:31,960
not handled carefully, the consequences

15
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:34,239
can be

16
00:00:31,960 --> 00:00:36,320
disastrous. Today we're going to talk

17
00:00:34,239 --> 00:00:38,239
about race conditions, one of the most

18
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:41,320
bizarre and elusive bugs you can

19
00:00:38,239 --> 00:00:43,760
encounter in systems

20
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:48,399
programming. Hi friends, my name is

21
00:00:43,760 --> 00:00:50,399
George and this is core dumped.

22
00:00:48,399 --> 00:00:51,879
When we first learn programming, many of

23
00:00:50,399 --> 00:00:54,160
us are told we're simply writing

24
00:00:51,879 --> 00:00:55,760
instructions, defining one step after

25
00:00:54,160 --> 00:00:58,480
another for the computer to follow to

26
00:00:55,760 --> 00:01:00,239
reach a goal. What most beginners aren't

27
00:00:58,480 --> 00:01:02,520
told is that each line of code doesn't

28
00:01:00,239 --> 00:01:04,799
necessarily correspond to a single CPU

29
00:01:02,520 --> 00:01:06,080
instruction. In practice, some lines

30
00:01:04,799 --> 00:01:08,880
might compile down to just one

31
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:10,720
instruction, while others require many.

32
00:01:08,880 --> 00:01:13,040
Adding two numbers, for example,

33
00:01:10,720 --> 00:01:15,200
requires several instructions. one to

34
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:17,600
fetch each operin from memory into CPU

35
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:19,759
registers, another to tell the CPU to

36
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:21,439
add the values in those registers, and a

37
00:01:19,759 --> 00:01:23,360
final instruction to store the result

38
00:01:21,439 --> 00:01:25,439
back into memory so the value can be

39
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:27,280
accessed later. As good systems

40
00:01:25,439 --> 00:01:29,360
programmers, we must keep in mind that

41
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:31,520
most operations we write in source code

42
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:34,079
require multiple CPU steps to accomplish

43
00:01:31,520 --> 00:01:35,759
what we intend them to do. And this is

44
00:01:34,079 --> 00:01:38,000
the first critical concept to know if

45
00:01:35,759 --> 00:01:41,119
you want to understand race conditions.

46
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,880
Most operations are not atomic.

47
00:01:41,119 --> 00:01:45,439
Now let's refresh some concepts we've

48
00:01:42,880 --> 00:01:46,799
covered before. We've previously

49
00:01:45,439 --> 00:01:49,520
discussed that threads are usually

50
00:01:46,799 --> 00:01:51,520
created through system calls. In C, for

51
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:53,439
example, the most common way to create

52
00:01:51,520 --> 00:01:56,200
threads is with the Pthread create

53
00:01:53,439 --> 00:01:58,320
function available on PZIX compliant

54
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:59,960
systems. This function receives a

55
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:02,880
pointer to another

56
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:05,280
function. When we call Pthread create, a

57
00:02:02,880 --> 00:02:07,119
lot happens under the hood. The inner

58
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:08,879
system call informs the operating system

59
00:02:07,119 --> 00:02:10,239
that the function passed as a parameter

60
00:02:08,879 --> 00:02:12,560
can start running as a separate

61
00:02:10,239 --> 00:02:14,640
executable entity running concurrently

62
00:02:12,560 --> 00:02:17,200
with the thread that made the call. So

63
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:18,879
in our example after the system call the

64
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:21,319
main function continues running without

65
00:02:18,879 --> 00:02:23,920
waiting for the newly created thread to

66
00:02:21,319 --> 00:02:26,400
finish. Also remember concurrency does

67
00:02:23,920 --> 00:02:28,400
not imply parallelism. In a multi-core

68
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:30,959
system concurrent functions may execute

69
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:33,440
in parallel but on a single core system

70
00:02:30,959 --> 00:02:35,920
the CPU core is shared. Each thread

71
00:02:33,440 --> 00:02:37,440
takes turns. The switching happens so

72
00:02:35,920 --> 00:02:39,000
quickly that it appears as if they're

73
00:02:37,440 --> 00:02:41,200
running

74
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,879
simultaneously. There are many use cases

75
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:45,519
where threads and concurrency are

76
00:02:42,879 --> 00:02:48,000
incredibly useful. For example, modern

77
00:02:45,519 --> 00:02:49,920
HTTP servers rely heavily on threads to

78
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,599
handle multiple client requests at the

79
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:53,280
same

80
00:02:50,599 --> 00:02:55,040
time. Without concurrency, the main

81
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:56,959
function would have to serve each client

82
00:02:55,040 --> 00:02:59,120
request before even accepting another

83
00:02:56,959 --> 00:03:01,920
client's request. You can imagine how

84
00:02:59,120 --> 00:03:03,840
inefficient that would be.

85
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:06,080
With concurrency, the main thread

86
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:08,000
listens for incoming requests. And as

87
00:03:06,080 --> 00:03:10,560
soon as one arrives, it spawns a new

88
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,879
thread to handle it. Since that thread

89
00:03:10,560 --> 00:03:15,560
operates independently, the main thread

90
00:03:12,879 --> 00:03:17,680
can go back to listening for new

91
00:03:15,560 --> 00:03:20,120
requests. But despite how useful

92
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:22,319
concurrency is, it must be used with

93
00:03:20,120 --> 00:03:24,239
caution. Let's say the server returns

94
00:03:22,319 --> 00:03:26,720
the name of the client sent in the body

95
00:03:24,239 --> 00:03:28,400
of the request. In this case, each

96
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:30,640
thread only deals with its own client

97
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:33,959
and doesn't interact with others. Since

98
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:36,400
there's no shared data, not much can go

99
00:03:33,959 --> 00:03:39,040
wrong. But what if threads need to share

100
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:40,640
and modify the same data? Imagine that

101
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:42,799
instead of replying with the client's

102
00:03:40,640 --> 00:03:45,040
name, the server returns a string shared

103
00:03:42,799 --> 00:03:46,720
by all threads, one that's periodically

104
00:03:45,040 --> 00:03:48,680
updated from a list of sentences by

105
00:03:46,720 --> 00:03:51,360
another

106
00:03:48,680 --> 00:03:54,920
thread. In this scenario, threads need

107
00:03:51,360 --> 00:03:54,920
some way to communicate.

108
00:03:56,319 --> 00:03:59,280
But almost everyone new to concurrency

109
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,360
will fail at implementing this

110
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:03,280
correctly. Many will define a global

111
00:04:01,360 --> 00:04:04,799
variable to store the current string,

112
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:06,959
create a function that periodically

113
00:04:04,799 --> 00:04:09,680
updates it, and spawn a thread that runs

114
00:04:06,959 --> 00:04:11,760
this function. The writer thread simply

115
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:13,200
modifies this variable as needed, while

116
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:14,720
the handler threads read from it

117
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:17,120
whenever they need to respond to a

118
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:19,440
client. And this is exactly what I tried

119
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:21,199
on my own machine. I defined a shared

120
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:23,280
variable, hard-coded a list of

121
00:04:21,199 --> 00:04:26,759
sentences, and the writer thread cycles

122
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:29,280
through that list, updating the shared

123
00:04:26,759 --> 00:04:30,960
variable. To observe the behavior, I

124
00:04:29,280 --> 00:04:33,240
logged every response that the handler

125
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:36,080
thread sent back to clients into a text

126
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:38,080
file. At first glance, everything looked

127
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:41,040
fine. The writer thread appeared to

128
00:04:38,080 --> 00:04:42,759
update the string periodically. But then

129
00:04:41,040 --> 00:04:45,280
I found

130
00:04:42,759 --> 00:04:47,840
this. One response returned a string

131
00:04:45,280 --> 00:04:49,600
that was not in the list I hard-coded.

132
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:52,199
For some reason, the last letter was

133
00:04:49,600 --> 00:04:54,560
different. Something had clearly gone

134
00:04:52,199 --> 00:04:56,000
wrong. Now, just looking at this single

135
00:04:54,560 --> 00:04:58,479
instance isn't enough to draw

136
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:01,360
conclusions. It happened once in over 9

137
00:04:58,479 --> 00:05:02,960
million requests. In fact, it would have

138
00:05:01,360 --> 00:05:05,040
been nearly impossible to notice by

139
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:06,639
scrolling through the logs. I only found

140
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:08,400
it because I knew exactly what I was

141
00:05:06,639 --> 00:05:10,560
looking for and wrote a program to

142
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:12,960
search for anomalies.

143
00:05:10,560 --> 00:05:15,120
So, I ran the test again, this time for

144
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:17,840
much longer, and analyzed the results

145
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:19,520
with the same program. After nearly 85

146
00:05:17,840 --> 00:05:22,000
million requests, I found more

147
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:23,639
suspicious outputs. And this time, the

148
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,080
issue was a little more

149
00:05:23,639 --> 00:05:27,600
obvious. To make it clearer, I'll assign

150
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:29,639
a different color to each sentence from

151
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:31,840
the list so you can see exactly what's

152
00:05:29,639 --> 00:05:33,680
happening. It turns out that in some

153
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:35,960
responses, the server was sending

154
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:39,199
combinations of different

155
00:05:35,960 --> 00:05:40,880
sentences. So, what's going on here?

156
00:05:39,199 --> 00:05:42,720
This is one of those rare cases where

157
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:44,960
the program misbehaves not because our

158
00:05:42,720 --> 00:05:46,840
logic is flawed, but because we ignored

159
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:48,800
how the system works

160
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:50,639
underneath. We'll cover the source of

161
