201
00:07:21,599 --> 00:07:26,720
And now back to the

202
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:28,639
video. To understand why our program is

203
00:07:26,720 --> 00:07:31,520
behaving so strangely, we need to look

204
00:07:28,639 --> 00:07:33,360
at how strings work. Believe it or not,

205
00:07:31,520 --> 00:07:35,840
the string data type deserves its own

206
00:07:33,360 --> 00:07:38,560
dedicated video. But for simplicity,

207
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:40,639
we're going to focus on C style strings.

208
00:07:38,560 --> 00:07:42,400
In summary, in C, strings are

209
00:07:40,639 --> 00:07:44,319
represented in memory as a sequence of

210
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:45,919
characters terminated by a special null

211
00:07:44,319 --> 00:07:47,599
character.

212
00:07:45,919 --> 00:07:49,120
This null character is convenient

213
00:07:47,599 --> 00:07:51,360
because it eliminates the need to store

214
00:07:49,120 --> 00:07:53,560
both a pointer and the string's length

215
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:55,759
as is done in some object-oriented

216
00:07:53,560 --> 00:07:57,759
languages. What's pertinent to us right

217
00:07:55,759 --> 00:08:00,720
now is that most string operations are

218
00:07:57,759 --> 00:08:02,400
not atomic. For example, when printing a

219
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:04,479
string, the function iterates through

220
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:06,160
the characters one by one, outputting

221
00:08:04,479 --> 00:08:08,639
them to the console until it encounters

222
00:08:06,160 --> 00:08:08,639
the null

223
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:14,319
character. Similarly, copying a string

224
00:08:11,840 --> 00:08:15,919
is a multi-step operation. If the string

225
00:08:14,319 --> 00:08:17,520
is long enough, the computer can't

226
00:08:15,919 --> 00:08:19,360
simply copy the entire array of

227
00:08:17,520 --> 00:08:21,919
characters from one memory location to

228
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:23,599
another in a single step. Instead, it

229
00:08:21,919 --> 00:08:25,520
has to loop through each character,

230
00:08:23,599 --> 00:08:27,240
copying them one by one until it reaches

231
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:29,599
the null

232
00:08:27,240 --> 00:08:32,000
terminator. Now, to speed up this

233
00:08:29,599 --> 00:08:34,399
process, some architectures copy data in

234
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:36,399
chunks. But even then, those chunks have

235
00:08:34,399 --> 00:08:38,479
a maximum size, and depending on the

236
00:08:36,399 --> 00:08:41,039
length of the string, the operation may

237
00:08:38,479 --> 00:08:42,959
still require multiple steps. For

238
00:08:41,039 --> 00:08:45,519
simplicity, let's stick to the character

239
00:08:42,959 --> 00:08:47,200
by character approach. The reason I

240
00:08:45,519 --> 00:08:48,720
chose this example is that it clearly

241
00:08:47,200 --> 00:08:51,600
demonstrates what's happening under the

242
00:08:48,720 --> 00:08:53,200
hood. Just think about it. If one thread

243
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:55,360
is reading from the shared string while

244
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:56,880
another is writing to it, concurrency

245
00:08:55,360 --> 00:08:59,040
can cause the operating system to

246
00:08:56,880 --> 00:09:02,000
interrupt the writer midcopy to give the

247
00:08:59,040 --> 00:09:04,000
CPU to another process. When this

248
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:06,240
happens, the shared string is said to be

249
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:08,000
in an invalid state because its current

250
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:10,320
value is something we never intended it

251
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:12,399
to be. And if the scheduler decides to

252
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:14,399
allocate the CPU to a thread that reads

253
00:09:12,399 --> 00:09:16,640
this shared data before the writer

254
00:09:14,399 --> 00:09:18,160
thread resumes and completes its update,

255
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:20,880
that thread will end up copying

256
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:20,880
inconsistent

257
00:09:22,680 --> 00:09:27,519
data. And that's exactly what happened

258
00:09:25,120 --> 00:09:29,120
in our example. While modifying the

259
00:09:27,519 --> 00:09:31,120
string, the writer thread was

260
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:33,040
interrupted and the threads handling

261
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:37,160
client requests ended up copying the

262
00:09:33,040 --> 00:09:37,160
string while it was still incomplete.

263
00:09:37,839 --> 00:09:41,120
That's why all the errors show strings

264
00:09:39,600 --> 00:09:44,240
composed of fragments from different

265
00:09:41,120 --> 00:09:44,240
valid sentences in the

266
00:09:44,680 --> 00:09:49,040
list. A race condition is a software bug

267
00:09:47,519 --> 00:09:50,880
that occurs when the outcome of a

268
00:09:49,040 --> 00:09:53,120
program depends on the unpredictable

269
00:09:50,880 --> 00:09:56,200
order in which multiple threads or

270
00:09:53,120 --> 00:09:58,480
processes access and modify shared

271
00:09:56,200 --> 00:10:00,279
resources. Race conditions are typically

272
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:02,720
side effects of preemptive operating

273
00:10:00,279 --> 00:10:04,399
systems. There lies the unpredictable

274
00:10:02,720 --> 00:10:06,959
requirement for this kind of bug to

275
00:10:04,399 --> 00:10:08,720
occur. For those unfamiliar, a

276
00:10:06,959 --> 00:10:10,640
preemptive operating system is one that

277
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:12,399
forcibly interrupts running processes

278
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:15,120
from time to time so that other

279
00:10:12,399 --> 00:10:16,640
processes can gain access to the CPU.

280
00:10:15,120 --> 00:10:18,560
This is how the system distributes

281
00:10:16,640 --> 00:10:20,959
computing resources fairly among all

282
00:10:18,560 --> 00:10:23,120
active programs. When we talked about

283
00:10:20,959 --> 00:10:25,200
CPU scheduling, we mentioned the time

284
00:10:23,120 --> 00:10:27,440
quantum, a fixed amount of time that

285
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:29,399
defines how long a process or thread can

286
00:10:27,440 --> 00:10:31,680
use the CPU before it may be

287
00:10:29,399 --> 00:10:33,519
interrupted. Through system calls,

288
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:35,839
processes and threads can voluntarily

289
00:10:33,519 --> 00:10:38,800
yield control of the CPU to allow others

290
00:10:35,839 --> 00:10:40,480
to run. But if a thread or process

291
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:42,800
doesn't finish its current task before

292
00:10:40,480 --> 00:10:44,640
its quantum expires, a hardware timer

293
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:47,200
triggers an interrupt that preempts the

294
00:10:44,640 --> 00:10:49,480
process, meaning the OS pauses it and

295
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:52,399
reallocates the CPU to something

296
00:10:49,480 --> 00:10:54,480
else. So if a data modification takes

297
00:10:52,399 --> 00:10:56,880
longer than one time quantum, the data

298
00:10:54,480 --> 00:10:58,480
will inevitably enter an invalid state

299
00:10:56,880 --> 00:11:00,720
because at least one interruption is

300
00:10:58,480 --> 00:11:02,320
guaranteed.

301
00:11:00,720 --> 00:11:04,399
However, that doesn't mean shorter

302
00:11:02,320 --> 00:11:06,240
operations are safe. Even if a data

303
00:11:04,399 --> 00:11:08,519
modification completes in less than one

304
00:11:06,240 --> 00:11:11,920
time quantum, race conditions can still

305
00:11:08,519 --> 00:11:13,680
occur. Why? Well, for starters, if the

306
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:15,720
operation begins near the end of a time

307
00:11:13,680 --> 00:11:18,320
quantum, it's highly likely to be

308
00:11:15,720 --> 00:11:20,480
interrupted. But beyond timing issues,

309
00:11:18,320 --> 00:11:23,760
the CPU can be interrupted by many other

310
00:11:20,480 --> 00:11:26,800
events that aren't tied to theuler.

311
00:11:23,760 --> 00:11:29,440
timers set by other processes. A user

312
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:31,600
pressing a button in a UI, an incoming

313
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:33,600
network packet. There are all kind of

314
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:35,760
events that trigger interrupts. And

315
00:11:33,600 --> 00:11:37,279
interrupts regardless of their origin

316
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:39,640
can preempt the currently running

317
00:11:37,279 --> 00:11:42,240
thread, even if it's time quantum hasn't

318
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:44,160
expired. And unfortunately, we can't

319
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:46,079
prevent those events from occurring. At

320
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:47,760
least not without making the system less

321
00:11:46,079 --> 00:11:50,399
responsive to the very events those

322
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:51,839
interrupts are meant to handle. But can

323
00:11:50,399 --> 00:11:53,600
we at least try to prevent them from

324
00:11:51,839 --> 00:11:56,000
corrupting our data?

325
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:58,000
Let's go back to our example and try.

326
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:00,320
Before continuing, consider giving this

327
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:02,640
video a like. It helps others discover

328
00:12:00,320 --> 00:12:03,720
my content, which by the way is

329
00:12:02,640 --> 00:12:06,079
completely

330
00:12:03,720 --> 00:12:08,639
free. What if we introduce a control

331
00:12:06,079 --> 00:12:10,600
variable, a flag that indicates whether

332
00:12:08,639 --> 00:12:13,040
the shared data is currently being

333
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:16,320
modified. For example, one means

334
00:12:13,040 --> 00:12:18,079
writing, zero means not writing. With

335
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:19,680
this setup, threads that want to read

336
00:12:18,079 --> 00:12:21,440
from the shared string can first check

337
00:12:19,680 --> 00:12:22,920
the flag to see if the writer thread is

338
00:12:21,440 --> 00:12:25,440
currently modifying

339
00:12:22,920 --> 00:12:27,760
it. Now, while this might sound like a

340
00:12:25,440 --> 00:12:29,519
good idea, we need to be cautious

341
00:12:27,760 --> 00:12:31,600
because the moment this control variable

342
00:12:29,519 --> 00:12:33,760
is shared between threads, it becomes

343
00:12:31,600 --> 00:12:35,240
shared data and is therefore also

344
00:12:33,760 --> 00:12:37,200
vulnerable to race

345
00:12:35,240 --> 00:12:39,839
conditions. Setting or checking a

346
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:41,839
variable's value is not always atomic.

347
00:12:39,839 --> 00:12:44,399
On some architectures, writing to a

348
00:12:41,839 --> 00:12:47,040
variable may be atomic, but reading and

349
00:12:44,399 --> 00:12:49,040
comparing its value almost never is.

350
00:12:47,040 --> 00:12:51,040
This typically involves loading the

351
00:12:49,040 --> 00:12:53,200
variable's value from memory into a

352
00:12:51,040 --> 00:12:55,399
register, comparing that register's

353
00:12:53,200 --> 00:13:00,000
value to some constant or expected

354
00:12:55,399 --> 00:13:00,000
value, then acting on the result of that

355
00:13:01,399 --> 00:13:06,880
comparison. Imagine this situation. A

356
00:13:04,160 --> 00:13:08,480
reader thread checks the flag. It loads

357
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:11,399
the value into a register but right

358
00:13:08,480 --> 00:13:14,000
after the comparison it gets

359
00:13:11,399 --> 00:13:16,079
interrupted. Then the writer thread sets

360
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,920
the flag to one and starts modifying the

361
00:13:16,079 --> 00:13:19,320
shared string but it also gets

362
00:13:17,920 --> 00:13:21,600
interrupted before

363
00:13:19,320 --> 00:13:23,440
finishing. Then when the reader thread

364
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:25,200
is dispatched again, its state is

365
00:13:23,440 --> 00:13:27,519
restored. So it continues right where it

366
00:13:25,200 --> 00:13:30,079
left off still holding the old value of

367
00:13:27,519 --> 00:13:31,680
the flag in its register. Since this

368
00:13:30,079 --> 00:13:33,519
thread fetched the value of the flag

369
00:13:31,680 --> 00:13:35,200
before the writer thread modifies it,

370
00:13:33,519 --> 00:13:37,839
the comparison is now based on an

371
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:39,519
outdated value. As a result, the thread

372
00:13:37,839 --> 00:13:41,519
mistakenly believes it's safe to read

373
00:13:39,519 --> 00:13:44,800
the shared string even though the data

374
00:13:41,519 --> 00:13:46,839
is in an invalid state and our variable

375
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:49,279
didn't really help that

376
00:13:46,839 --> 00:13:51,279
much. So unless we really know what

377
00:13:49,279 --> 00:13:53,360
we're doing, using regular variables as

378
00:13:51,279 --> 00:13:55,600
flags to control access to shared data

379
00:13:53,360 --> 00:13:56,959
should be avoided. The reason I bring

380
00:13:55,600 --> 00:13:59,440
this up is because there are some

381
00:13:56,959 --> 00:14:01,600
classic software-based solutions like

382
00:13:59,440 --> 00:14:03,680
this one called the Peterson solution

383
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:05,800
that rely on many subtle assumptions to

384
00:14:03,680 --> 00:14:08,079
work correctly in very specific

385
00:14:05,800 --> 00:14:09,800
situations. These include details like

386
00:14:08,079 --> 00:14:11,959
software behavior, compiler

387
00:14:09,800 --> 00:14:13,920
optimizations, and even hardware

388
00:14:11,959 --> 00:14:15,959
architecture. I'll talk about this with

389
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:18,000
more details in my video about thread

390
00:14:15,959 --> 00:14:20,959
synchronization. For now, let's keep

391
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:22,320
talking about race conditions. So far,

392
00:14:20,959 --> 00:14:24,480
we've looked at the case where one

393
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:26,440
thread writes to shared data while other

394
00:14:24,480 --> 00:14:28,880
threads only read from

395
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:30,399
it. But there are also cases where

396
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:32,800
multiple threads need to write to the

397
00:14:30,399 --> 00:14:35,639
shared data at the same time. In these

398
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:37,760
cases, race conditions are just as

399
00:14:35,639 --> 00:14:39,600
dangerous. Think about a program that

400
00:14:37,760 --> 00:14:41,680
receives a number and finds how many

401
00:14:39,600 --> 00:14:44,800
prime numbers exist between zero and

402
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:46,880
that number. Parallelism is used to make

403
00:14:44,800 --> 00:14:50,480
the process faster so each thread can

404
00:14:46,880 --> 00:14:52,639
run in a separate CPU core. To do this,

405
00:14:50,480 --> 00:14:54,480
the threads use a shared counter, an

406
00:14:52,639 --> 00:14:57,680
integer that gets incremented each time

407
00:14:54,480 --> 00:14:57,680
a thread finds a prime

408
00:14:58,199 --> 00:15:02,639
number. The problem is that in many

409
00:15:00,480 --> 00:15:05,680
architectures, incrementing a value is

410
00:15:02,639 --> 00:15:07,440
not an atomic operation. If two threads

411
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:09,440
in this example find prime numbers at

412
00:15:07,440 --> 00:15:11,079
nearly the same time, we expect the

413
00:15:09,440 --> 00:15:13,360
count to increase to

414
00:15:11,079 --> 00:15:15,440
459. But since they are running in

415
00:15:13,360 --> 00:15:18,160
parallel, they might both fetch the same

416
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:20,480
value, increment it independently, and

417
00:15:18,160 --> 00:15:22,720
write the result back, resulting in the

418
00:15:20,480 --> 00:15:25,279
counter only increasing by one, even

419
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:27,519
though two primes were found. And no

420
00:15:25,279 --> 00:15:28,720
interrupt took part here. The race

421
00:15:27,519 --> 00:15:31,440
condition happened because of the

422
00:15:28,720 --> 00:15:32,800
parallel access to the shared variable.

423
00:15:31,440 --> 00:15:35,120
But that doesn't mean things would have

424
00:15:32,800 --> 00:15:37,600
gone better without parallelism. Here's

425
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:39,839
a simple scenario. Let's say the program

426
00:15:37,600 --> 00:15:42,240
has already found 10 prime numbers.

427
00:15:39,839 --> 00:15:44,880
Suddenly, five threads all find prime

428
00:15:42,240 --> 00:15:47,920
numbers at roughly the same time. The

429
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:50,199
expected count afterward should be 15.

430
00:15:47,920 --> 00:15:52,639
But watch what might

431
00:15:50,199 --> 00:15:54,639
happen. Suppose the first thread fetches

432
00:15:52,639 --> 00:15:56,079
the count and increments it, but is

433
00:15:54,639 --> 00:15:58,600
interrupted right before writing the

434
00:15:56,079 --> 00:16:01,440
result back to

435
00:15:58,600 --> 00:16:03,120
memory. And then the other four threads

436
00:16:01,440 --> 00:16:05,279
run without interruption. Each

437
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:09,240
successfully incrementing the count. So

438
00:16:05,279 --> 00:16:09,240
the counter reaches 14.

439
00:16:12,560 --> 00:16:16,399
Then the first thread resumes exactly

440
00:16:14,639 --> 00:16:18,000
where it left off, right before the

441
00:16:16,399 --> 00:16:20,079
instruction to store the incremented

442
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:21,759
value back to memory. But since that

443
00:16:20,079 --> 00:16:23,920
value was calculated before the other

444
00:16:21,759 --> 00:16:26,000
four threads incremented the counter, it

445
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:28,160
overwrites the updated result, causing

446
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:31,120
the count to drop from 14 back down to

447
00:16:28,160 --> 00:16:35,320
11. And just like that, four correctly

448
00:16:31,120 --> 00:16:35,320
detected prime numbers are lost.

449
00:16:35,360 --> 00:16:39,759
This kind of behavior feels bizarre.

450
00:16:38,240 --> 00:16:42,360
People usually think of computers as

451
00:16:39,759 --> 00:16:44,880
being amazing at math, fast, smart,

452
00:16:42,360 --> 00:16:47,199
sophisticated. But in truth, computers

453
00:16:44,880 --> 00:16:49,120
are dumb. They don't recognize these

454
00:16:47,199 --> 00:16:50,639
situations. They blindly follow

455
00:16:49,120 --> 00:16:53,120
instructions even when those

456
00:16:50,639 --> 00:16:54,880
instructions cause problems. And if

457
00:16:53,120 --> 00:16:57,279
that's not bizarre enough, check this

458
00:16:54,880 --> 00:16:59,360
out. If I run the same program multiple

459
00:16:57,279 --> 00:17:02,000
times, I get a different result almost

460
00:16:59,360 --> 00:17:04,959
every single time. sometimes even

461
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:06,640
getting the right result. Why? Because

462
00:17:04,959 --> 00:17:07,839
the behavior of the program depends on

463
00:17:06,640 --> 00:17:10,480
the timing and sequence of

464
00:17:07,839 --> 00:17:12,480
uncontrollable events. There's no way to

465
00:17:10,480 --> 00:17:14,439
predict when those events will occur.

466
00:17:12,480 --> 00:17:16,640
That's what makes race conditions so

467
00:17:14,439 --> 00:17:18,480
dangerous. It's called a race condition

468
00:17:16,640 --> 00:17:20,880
because multiple operations race to

469
00:17:18,480 --> 00:17:22,400
access or modify shared data and the

470
00:17:20,880 --> 00:17:23,480
final result depends on which one

471
00:17:22,400 --> 00:17:25,839
finishes

472
00:17:23,480 --> 00:17:26,720
first. Finally, I want to emphasize

473
00:17:25,839 --> 00:17:28,960
something that might seem

474
00:17:26,720 --> 00:17:31,280
counterintuitive. The most dangerous

475
00:17:28,960 --> 00:17:34,640
thing about race conditions is how rare

476
00:17:31,280 --> 00:17:36,640
they are. In my server example, only 14

477
00:17:34,640 --> 00:17:39,240
incidents occurred out of 85 million

478
00:17:36,640 --> 00:17:41,120
requests. That's an incredibly small

479
00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:44,480
probability. And that's what makes them

480
00:17:41,120 --> 00:17:46,799
so hard to reproduce and debug. So the

481
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:49,039
next time your project uses concurrency,

482
00:17:46,799 --> 00:17:50,640
remember if you're not careful, every

483
00:17:49,039 --> 00:17:53,200
thread you spawn might be starting the

484
00:17:50,640 --> 00:17:55,679
countdown on a time bomb. In the best

485
00:17:53,200 --> 00:17:57,440
case scenario, your program will crash.

486
00:17:55,679 --> 00:18:00,080
In the worst case, there's no telling

487
00:17:57,440 --> 00:18:01,679
what it might end up doing. Fortunately,

488
00:18:00,080 --> 00:18:03,760
computers provide tools to help us

489
00:18:01,679 --> 00:18:06,080
prevent race conditions, but that's a

490
00:18:03,760 --> 00:18:07,679
topic for a future episode. So, make

491
00:18:06,080 --> 00:18:10,160
sure to subscribe. You don't want to

492
00:18:07,679 --> 00:18:12,240
miss it. Thanks to Flexispot for

493
00:18:10,160 --> 00:18:14,480
sponsoring this video. Don't forget to

494
00:18:12,240 --> 00:18:16,320
check out the E7 Pro standing desk and

495
00:18:14,480 --> 00:18:20,240
the treadmill. Both are linked in the

496
00:18:16,320 --> 00:18:20,240
description below. See you in the next

